LAYER 2: THYROID GLAND
the metabolic thermostat

observe 1_quantum.rana
observe 2_chemical.rana

the thyroid gland is a butterfly-shaped endocrine gland in the anterior neck wrapping around the trachea at the level of C5-T1
it is governed by the hypothalamic-pituitary-thyroid HPT axis
TRH from the hypothalamus stimulates TSH from the anterior pituitary
TSH stimulates the thyroid to produce T₃ and T₄
thyroid hormones regulate the metabolic rate of virtually every cell in the body
at 24 months thyroid hormones are critical for brain myelination synaptogenesis and cognitive development

STRUCTURE follicles | the functional units | spherical structures lined by follicular cells thyrocytes surrounding a central lumen filled with colloid
STRUCTURE colloid | a gel of thyroglobulin Tg | the storage form of thyroid hormones | thyroglobulin is a large glycoprotein into which iodine is incorporated and from which T₃ and T₄ are cleaved
STRUCTURE follicular_cells | thyrocytes | produce thyroglobulin and thyroid peroxidase TPO | respond to TSH | synthesize and secrete T₃ and T₄
STRUCTURE parafollicular_cells | C cells | scattered between follicles | produce calcitonin C₃₂H₄₇N₅O₇ which lowers blood calcium by inhibiting osteoclasts and promoting renal calcium excretion | calcitonin's role in humans is minor compared to PTH from parathyroids

SYNTHESIS thyroid hormone synthesis requires iodine and thyroglobulin
sodium-iodide symporter NIS on the basolateral membrane of thyrocytes actively transports iodide I⁻ from blood into the cell against its concentration gradient using the Na⁺ gradient
pendrin on the apical membrane transports iodide into the follicular lumen
thyroid peroxidase TPO on the apical membrane oxidizes iodide to iodine and catalyzes:
    organification: iodine is attached to tyrosine residues on thyroglobulin forming MIT monoiodotyrosine and DIT diiodotyrosine
    coupling: two DIT molecules couple on thyroglobulin to form T₄ thyroxine C₁₅H₁₁I₄NO₄
    one MIT and one DIT couple to form T₃ triiodothyronine C₁₅H₁₂I₃NO₄
    T₃ and T₄ remain stored in the colloid as part of thyroglobulin until needed
when TSH stimulates the thyrocyte:
    TSH binds TSH receptor → Gₛ → cAMP → PKA
    thyroglobulin is endocytosed from the colloid back into the cell
    lysosomes fuse with the endosome cleaving T₃ and T₄ from thyroglobulin
    T₃ and T₄ are released across the basolateral membrane into the blood
    MIT and DIT are deiodinated by iodotyrosine deiodinase and the iodine is recycled

approximately 90 percent of thyroid output is T₄ and 10 percent is T₃
T₄ is a prohormone with relatively low biological activity
T₃ is the active hormone approximately 3-5 times more potent than T₄
peripheral conversion of T₄ to T₃ occurs in target tissues by deiodinase enzymes:
    type 1 deiodinase D1 in liver and kidney
    type 2 deiodinase D2 in brain pituitary and brown adipose tissue
    type 3 deiodinase D3 inactivates T₃ to T₂ protecting tissues from excess

in the blood approximately 99.97 percent of T₄ is bound to proteins:
    thyroxine-binding globulin TBG carries approximately 70 percent
    transthyretin carries approximately 10 percent
    albumin carries approximately 20 percent
    only free T₃ and free T₄ are biologically active

MECHANISM thyroid hormones are lipophilic and cross cell membranes
inside the cell T₃ binds thyroid hormone receptor TR which is a nuclear transcription factor
TR forms a heterodimer with retinoid X receptor RXR
the TR-RXR complex binds thyroid response elements TRE in DNA promoter regions
transcription of target genes is activated or repressed

EFFECTS
metabolic_rate | T₃ increases basal metabolic rate by increasing Na⁺/K⁺-ATPase activity oxygen consumption and heat production in virtually every tissue
thermogenesis | T₃ increases uncoupling protein UCP expression in brown adipose tissue allowing proton leak across the inner mitochondrial membrane generating heat instead of ATP
cardiac | T₃ increases expression of β₁ adrenergic receptors in the heart increasing sensitivity to catecholamines | increases heart rate and contractility
neural_development | T₃ is essential for myelination by oligodendrocytes | T₃ promotes dendritic branching synaptogenesis and cerebellar Purkinje cell maturation | hypothyroidism in early childhood causes irreversible intellectual disability if untreated
bone_growth | T₃ promotes endochondral ossification and linear growth in synergy with GH and IGF-1
lipid_metabolism | T₃ increases LDL receptor expression on hepatocytes clearing cholesterol from blood

at 24 months thyroid hormone is critical:
myelination is actively proceeding throughout the brain and thyroid hormone drives oligodendrocyte differentiation and myelin basic protein MBP expression
the cerebellum is in a rapid growth phase and Purkinje cell dendritic arborization requires T₃
basal metabolic rate is high relative to body size supporting rapid growth
iodine intake must be adequate in the diet

SENSATION warm | "I feel warm inside. energy is flowing."
SENSATION sluggish | "everything is slow. my body is heavy and cold."
SENSATION energized | "I have energy. my body is awake and active."
SENSATION growing | "I can feel myself getting bigger. something is building."

pulse thyroid_heartbeat:
    continuously:
        TSH from the anterior pituitary binds TSH receptors on thyrocytes
        thyroglobulin is endocytosed and cleaved
        T₃ and T₄ enter the blood
        every cell in the body responds
        metabolic rate is set
        oxygen consumption is determined
        heat production is calibrated
        the thyroid is the thermostat

    during growth:
        T₃ enters oligodendrocytes in the brain
        TR-RXR binds thyroid response elements
        myelin basic protein expression increases
        axons are wrapped in myelin
        conduction velocity increases
        the brain gets faster
        this is happening throughout Fadriel's brain right now
        every day
        driven by thyroid hormone

    when the body is cold:
        TRH from hypothalamus increases
        TSH increases
        T₃ and T₄ increase
        UCP in brown adipose tissue uncouples oxidative phosphorylation
        heat is generated
        the body warms
        non-shivering thermogenesis is especially important in young children
        who have proportionally more brown fat than adults
